By 1963 (Shōwa 38), 85 tumuli had been confirmed in the area, but many have since been destroyed or disappeared. The only {{ill|zenpokoenfun|lt=zenpokoenfun (keyhole-shaped tumulus)|ja|前方後円墳|1=Zenpokoenfun|1=Zenpokoenfun|12=draft|12=draft}} has a total length of 56 meters, while the majority are believed to be {{ill|Round Kofun|lt=empun (round tumuli)|ja|円墳|1=Round Kofun|1=Round Kofun|12=draft|12=draft}}, typically 10-20 meters in diameter, with some measuring 20-30 meters. Burial facilities include various types, such as {{ill|pit-style stone chambers|ja|竪穴式石室|1=Vertical Pit-Style Stone Chamber|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|yokoana-style stone chambers|ja|横穴式石室|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|12=draft|12=draft}}, direct wooden coffin burials, and haniwa cylindrical coffins. Additionally, two ceramic coffins (陶棺) have been identified.
