'''Shinoda Senzuka Kofun Cluster''' (信太千塚古墳群) is a {{ill|kofun|ja|古墳|1=Kofun|12=draft|12=draft}} cluster from the late {{ill|Kofun period|ja|古墳時代|12=draft|12=draft}} located in the hilly areas of {{ill|Oi Town|ja|尾井町|12=draft|12=draft}}, Oji Town, Ono Town, Kurotori Town, Sanso Town, and Hakuta Town in {{ill|Izumi, Osaka|ja|和泉市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Osaka Prefecture|ja|大阪府|12=draft|12=draft}}.
== Overview ==
By 1963 (Shōwa 38), 85 tumuli had been confirmed in the area, but many have since been destroyed or disappeared. The only {{ill|zenpokoenfun|lt=zenpokoenfun (keyhole-shaped tumulus)|ja|前方後円墳|1=Zenpokoenfun|1=Zenpokoenfun|12=draft|12=draft}} has a total length of 56 meters, while the majority are believed to be {{ill|Round Kofun|lt=empun (round tumuli)|ja|円墳|1=Round Kofun|1=Round Kofun|12=draft|12=draft}}, typically 10-20 meters in diameter, with some measuring 20-30 meters. Burial facilities include various types, such as {{ill|pit-style stone chambers|ja|竪穴式石室|1=Vertical Pit-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=竪穴式石室|4=zh|5=豎穴式石室|1=Vertical Pit-Style Stone Chamber|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|yokoana-style stone chambers|ja|横穴式石室|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|12=draft|12=draft}}, direct wooden coffin burials, and haniwa cylindrical coffins. Additionally, two ceramic coffins (陶棺) have been identified.
Artifacts buried as grave goods are generally sparse per tumulus but include weapons (swords and arrowheads), agricultural tools (sickles), horse trappings, ornaments (gold and silver-plated earrings and beads), and {{ill|Sue pottery|ja|須恵器|1=Sue pottery|12=draft|12=draft}}. Among the excavated tumuli, the most representative is Kofun No. 78. The stone chamber of this horizontal tomb is constructed mainly from Izumi sandstone, housing a {{ill|hakogata sekkan (box-shaped stone coffin)|ja|箱式石棺|12=draft|12=draft}} made of metamorphic rock common in the {{ill|Kinokawa River|ja|紀ノ川|12=draft|12=draft}} basin of {{ill|Wakayama Prefecture|ja|和歌山県|12=draft|12=draft}}. At least three burials were conducted inside and outside the stone coffin, with grave goods including gold and silver earrings and numerous Sue pottery pieces.
A distinctive feature of this cluster is the presence of "kamado Kofuns" (カマド塚). These mounds employed a method in which a wooden kiln-like burial chamber was covered in clay, cremating the remains and simultaneously firing the chamber into a hardened state. Two such examples have been investigated within this cluster. Despite the significant loss of tumuli, the Shinoda Senzuka Kofun Cluster, along with the {{ill|Tokai Senzuka Kofun Cluster|ja|陶器千塚古墳群|12=draft|12=draft}} in Sakai City, represents a quintessential kofun cluster in the {{ill|Izumi Province|ja|和泉国|12=draft|12=draft}} region.
== Major Tumuli ==
The Kitsunezuka Kofun is a keyhole-shaped tumulus located beside the Sanso water distribution reservoir. It measures 56 meters in length, with the round portion measuring 30 meters in diameter and 4.5 meters in height, and the frontal portion 38 meters in width. Its wide frontal section suggests construction from the early to mid-late Kofun period.
Kofun No. 66, located within the Self-Defense Forces' Shinodayama base, is a large round tumulus with a diameter of 80 meters. It reportedly features a surrounding moat and a rectangular {{ill|Zōde|lt=protrusion|ja|造出|1=Platform-style projection|12=draft|12=draft}}, though these elements are no longer visible due to landfill. It is estimated to have been constructed during the mid to early late Kofun period<ref>Kuze (1968), pp. 7-10</ref>.
